üìú Why Serve-and-Volley Fell Out of Favor
Racket Technology Shift:
In the late '80s and early '90s, rackets moved from wood to graphite composites.
Players could hit with more power and topspin from the baseline, making it harder for net players to react in time.
String Technology:
The introduction of polyester strings allowed players to hit heavy topspin while maintaining control.
Passing shots and lobs became far more effective and consistent.
Court Surfaces Slowed Down:
Wimbledon literally changed the grass to slow it down after Sampras‚Äôs dominance.
The Australian Open switched to slower hard courts, and the French Open was always slow.
Physicality of the Game:
Modern tennis favors baseline grinders like Djokovic, Nadal, and Alcaraz, who can sustain long rallies and defend with insane flexibility and speed.
Serve-and-volley requires immaculate timing and the ability to close points quickly‚Äîriskier under today‚Äôs game dynamics.
Risk vs Reward Shift:
Players found that staying back and constructing points led to higher success percentages than the all-or-nothing gamble at the net.
But‚Ä¶ it‚Äôs not dead.
Players like Federer, Tsitsipas, and even Alcaraz use selective serve-and-volley tactics to great effect. You‚Äôll stand out as a beginner by embracing it‚Äîmost people stay glued to the baseline. You‚Äôll be a menace up there once you have quick reactions and control.

Would you like me to build a racket shortlist now, or add in a small serve-and-volley focused drill session first?

