Updated saved memory
Let‚Äôs break this down clearly and practically:

‚úã Continental Grip (a.k.a. ‚ÄúThe Chisel‚Äù for Net Play and Serving)
How to Find It:
Hold the racket like you‚Äôre shaking someone‚Äôs hand.
Your index knuckle should rest on Bevel #2 of the handle (imagine the racket handle as an 8-sided stop sign‚ÄîBevel #2 is slightly to the right if you‚Äôre right-handed).
When you look down, the racket face should be perpendicular to the ground.
What It‚Äôs Good For:
Volleys (block and redirect rather than swinging).
Serves (gives natural pronation and avoids wrist strain).
Overheads and slices.
Why It Feels Weird at First:
It‚Äôs not a natural feeling for groundstrokes, but it‚Äôs essential for quick reaction shots and serving without wrecking your shoulder or wrist.
üñêÔ∏è Alternative Grips (When You‚Äôre Ready)
Eastern Forehand Grip
Good for beginner baseline rallies.
Easier to learn flat shots with this.
Semi-Western Grip
Common for topspin-heavy baseline play.
Not ideal for volleys or beginner serving.
Eastern Backhand Grip
Used for one-handed backhands.
Two-Handed Backhand Grip
Most beginners default to this‚Äîleft hand controls, right hand supports (reverse if left-handed).
