Absolutely! Your preference for a one-handed backhand and a control-oriented playstyle is a solid foundation for developing an all-court game. Let's delve into the various tennis grips and how they align with your style.

üéæ Tennis Grip Overview
Tennis racket handles are octagonal, featuring eight bevels numbered clockwise for right-handed players (counterclockwise for left-handed players). The placement of your index knuckle and heel pad on these bevels determines your grip.

1. Continental Grip (Bevel #2)

Usage: Serves, volleys, overheads, slices.
Characteristics: Neutral grip allowing quick transitions between shots.
Ideal For: Net play and serve-and-volley strategies.
Visual Reference:
2. Eastern Forehand Grip (Bevel #3)

Usage: Forehand groundstrokes.
Characteristics: Offers a balance between flat shots and topspin.
Ideal For: Players seeking versatility and easy grip transitions.
Visual Reference:
3. Semi-Western Forehand Grip (Bevel #4)

Usage: Forehand groundstrokes with heavy topspin.
Characteristics: Allows for higher net clearance and aggressive topspin.
Ideal For: Baseline players who prefer topspin-heavy shots.
Visual Reference:
4. Eastern Backhand Grip (Bevel #1)

Usage: One-handed backhand strokes.
Characteristics: Facilitates flat and topspin shots with extended reach.
Ideal For: Players favoring a one-handed backhand.
Visual Reference:
üñêÔ∏è Grip Size Measurement
Selecting the correct grip size is crucial for comfort and injury prevention. Here's how to measure:

Ruler Test:
Open your dominant hand and extend your fingers.
Measure from the bottom lateral crease of your palm to the tip of your ring finger.
This measurement in inches corresponds to your grip size.
Index Finger Test:
Hold the racket with an Eastern forehand grip.
Insert the index finger of your non-dominant hand between your ring finger and palm.
A snug fit indicates the correct grip size.
Common Grip Sizes:

4 1/8" to 4 3/8": Smaller hands.
4 1/2" to 4 5/8": Larger hands.
Note: It's easier to increase grip size using overgrips than to decrease it.

üè∏ Racket Recommendations
Given your budget and playstyle, here are some rackets that align with your preferences:

Wilson Blade 98 (16x19) v8
Price: ~$199
Features: Excellent control and feel, suitable for players with a one-handed backhand.
Pros: Thin beam for better maneuverability; great for precision shots.
Head Gravity Tour
Price: ~$189
Features: Large sweet spot with a flexible frame.
Pros: Ideal for players seeking control and comfort.
Yonex VCORE Pro 97
Price: ~$199
Features: Exceptional control and spin potential.
Pros: Isometric head shape provides a larger sweet spot.
Note: Prices may vary based on retailers and ongoing promotions.

üìò Additional Resources
For a comprehensive understanding of tennis grips, you might find this video tutorial helpful:


This video provides visual demonstrations of various grips, which can be beneficial for your practice sessions.

Feel free to reach out if you need further assistance or personalized drills to enhance your game!


