However, following the Iranian Revolution in the late 1970s, tennis was banned, and Bahrami's career was abruptly halted. Determined to pursue his passion, he fled to France, where he faced numerous hardships, including homelessness and financial struggles. Despite these challenges, Bahrami's perseverance paid off. He became a successful doubles player, reaching the French Open doubles final in 1989 with partner √âric Winogradsky and achieving a career-high doubles ranking of World No. 31. 
