üéæ Quick Grip Transition Tip (Especially for Net Play)
When you‚Äôre rallying, you might use a forehand Eastern or Semi-Western grip.
But for net play, you‚Äôll want to quickly slide to the Continental grip (the ‚Äúhammer‚Äù grip) without hesitation.
Here‚Äôs the trick:

Keep your index knuckle aware of Bevel #2. After every groundstroke, let your hand slide slightly back to neutral along the handle.
Think of it like resting the racket gently in a handshake position between points‚Äîready to go wherever needed.
Practice just switching between grips without hitting balls for a few minutes a day. This wires your instincts.
üèÜ And Who Is Roland Garros?
He wasn‚Äôt a tennis player‚Äîhe was a French aviation pioneer and war hero.
Famous for being the first pilot to fly across the Mediterranean Sea (1913), and later, for his work developing forward-firing machine guns on fighter planes during WWI.
He died young, shot down in 1918, just before the end of the war.
So why his name on the French Open stadium and tournament?

It‚Äôs about honoring fearless innovation and grace under extreme conditions.
The stadium was built in 1928 and named after him to reflect the French spirit of daring and elegance.
It‚Äôs fitting, isn‚Äôt it? You‚Äôre literally playing with his name etched into your weapon of choice‚Äîa reminder that even in the heat of battle, there‚Äôs room for grace, boldness, and mastery over chaos.

