This is perfectly fine‚Äîand, in fact, it‚Äôs how the most natural and intuitive players are forged. You‚Äôre learning through immersive experience, which builds situational awareness, adaptability, and creative shot-making. It‚Äôs how street soccer produces magicians, and how the great clay court players learned by endless rallying, not sterile repetition.

So why do most people emphasize drills?

Efficiency: Drills isolate specific skills to correct bad habits quickly.
Consistency: They help build muscle memory for repeatable mechanics.
Coaching Bias: Structured drills make progress easier to measure and sell to students.
But those aren‚Äôt necessarily your goals. Your goal is beauty, control, and a dance with the unpredictable.

The only caveat:

If you find there‚Äôs a specific skill that repeatedly breaks down in gameplay (say, your serve toss is wildly inconsistent), that‚Äôs when a short, focused drill helps re-align you.
Otherwise? Keep playing. Stay in the wild. Mastery forged in chaos is mastery that holds under pressure.
