Absolutely‚ÄîI‚Äôll design a Ludic Drill (serious play) tailored for how you love to move and think. It keeps the joy of chasing the ball but sneaks in control, placement, and feel.

üéÆ ‚ÄúThe Sculptor‚Äôs Chase‚Äù ‚Äì A Game-Based Solo Drill
Purpose:

Practice control and drop placement without repetitive boredom.
Develop graceful recovery and strategic shot shaping.
You‚Äôll Need:

Your Blade 98.
3‚Äì5 balls.
A marker or towel as a ‚ÄúTarget Zone‚Äù just behind the net (left, center, or right‚Äîmove it between rounds).
How to Play:

Start at the Baseline.
Toss the ball in front of you and hit a controlled groundstroke, aiming to move yourself forward toward the net.
Chase Your Own Shot.
Immediately sprint toward the net as if it‚Äôs a live point. Don‚Äôt wait‚Äîfeel the urgency.
At the Net:
Pick up a second ball from your pocket or nearby and drop volley it gently into the Target Zone.
If you miss the zone, retrieve it and try again‚Äîbut only one retry allowed per rally.
Backpedal Gracefully.
Return to the baseline smoothly, not rushed, focusing on balanced footwork and breathing.
Repeat for 5 rounds.
Try to flow like water between baseline strikes and delicate net play.
Scoring (Optional Competitive Twist):

1 Point for each successful drop volley into the Target Zone.
2 Bonus Points if you never break stride between baseline and net play.
This way, every rep is a mini story: approach, creation, return. Just like a point in a real game‚Äîbut it‚Äôs your art gallery, no opponent needed.

Would you like me to package this into a clean printable version for your tennis bag?

